data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

Your code only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET 6+ breaking change. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

---

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort):

You could simplify this with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`:

```csharp
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This is purely a code quality improvement — the original is already safe on .NET 8.
